        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Although we calculated the S/N with 20 km/s velocity resolution, the HCN maser can have narrow velocity width. In that case, reducing the data with narrow velocity width makes the S/N higher due to less smoothing effect. We therefore take the data with ~4 km/s velocity resolution, and depends on the S/N of the HCN maser, we adjust the velocity width at the data reduction.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>M51 has a declination of +47deg and transits at the elevation of 20deg from the ALMA site. However, the lines we chose are the lowest frequencies (86-88 GHz) in the lowest band (Band 3), and the atmosphere is optically very thin even at low elevation (Matsushita et al. 1999, PASJ, 51, 603). The configuration we request is long baseline, so that we will not be affected by the shadowing. Our request, therefore, totally fullfil the requirements that are shown in the Proposers Guide and Technical Handbook. Furthermore, PI was one of the Expert Visitors of the whole ALMA Long Baseline Campaigns for the last 5 years, so we know all the technical details about the long baseline observations.

Based on the CASA Simulator (see Fig.3 of the Science Justification), the beam size is expected to be 0.3"x0.1" and the beam is elongated to north-south direction due to this low elevation. The source structures we would like to see are all along east-west direction, so the elongated beam does not affect our science goals at all.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_LOW_MAX_ELEVATION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To image the candidate HCN maser disk, we need highest spatial resolution. With this resolution, it is possible to image the velocity shift of high velocity components, if detected, and then from this velocity shift, it is possible to estimate the black hole mass. Although the target source is located north, we do not suffer any shadowing due to this long baseline configuration. Beam size will also be elongated because the source located north, but the HCN maser disk is expected to elongate east-west direction, which do not suffer the beam elongation.

The largest angular scale is set by the moleular gas along the radio jet. This is small enough to be recovered by the most extended configuration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to detect the high velocity component of the candidate HCN maser disk. In water maser disks, most of the high velocity components are about quarter of the systemic velocity component, so we adopt this value. The peak of the systemic velocity HCN maser component has been detected with 9.6 mJy/beam at the velocity width of 20 km/s, so the peak of the high velocity component is expected to be 2.4 mJy/beam. To detect this component with 5 sigma, we need 480 microJy/beam rms. Note that the maser is expected to be much smaller than the beam size, the target rms does not change with the beam size.

For the SiO emission, SiO will be enhanced at the shocked region and having its intensity of about 20-50% of the HCN intensity. Assuming the worse case of 20% and the requested rms mentioned above, it is possible to detect with 6 sigma. So, the above rms is enough to detect the SiO emission from shocked regions.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
